00:40:17.584 --> 00:40:18.610
(audience laughs)

00:40:18.610 --> 00:40:21.260
Okay, okay, so now I've signed it.

00:40:21.260 --> 00:40:22.300
I have a c4?

00:40:22.300 --> 00:40:24.030
- You have a c4, it's up and going.

00:40:24.030 --> 00:40:26.280
- So without this,

00:40:26.280 --> 00:40:28.760
I am transparent.

00:40:28.760 --> 00:40:31.065
With this, I am opaque.

00:40:31.065 --> 00:40:32.230
(audience laughs)
- That's it.

00:40:32.230 --> 00:40:34.133
- Without it, you get to know.

00:40:35.010 --> 00:40:37.800
With it, you go to hell.

00:40:37.800 --> 00:40:38.810
(Trevor and audience laugh)

00:40:38.810 --> 00:40:41.290
Without it, here's who gave me my money.

00:40:41.290 --> 00:40:42.520
With it, you know what?

00:40:42.520 --> 00:40:44.170
Your mother gave me my money.

00:40:44.170 --> 00:40:46.170
(Trevor and audience laugh)

00:40:46.170 --> 00:40:47.622
Well, I like that, Trev.

00:40:47.622 --> 00:40:50.840
(audience cheers)
(audience applauds)

00:40:50.840 --> 00:40:51.673
Okay.

00:40:52.680 --> 00:40:56.680
Okay, so now I can get
corporate, individual donations

00:40:56.680 --> 00:40:59.020
of unlimited amount for my c4.

00:40:59.020 --> 00:41:01.000
What can I do with that money?

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:03.970
- Well, that c4 could
take out political ads

00:41:03.970 --> 00:41:07.150
and attack candidates or
promote your favorite ones,

00:41:07.150 --> 00:41:09.660
as long as it's not the principle purpose

00:41:09.660 --> 00:41:10.700
for spending its money.

00:41:10.700 --> 00:41:13.813
- No, my principle purpose
is an educational entity.

00:41:13.813 --> 00:41:14.646
- There you go.

00:41:14.646 --> 00:41:16.943
- I wanna educate public that
gay people cause earthquakes.

00:41:16.943 --> 00:41:19.630
(audience laughs)

00:41:19.630 --> 00:41:21.100
- There are probably some c4s doing that.

00:41:21.100 --> 00:41:22.850
- Can I take this c4 money

00:41:22.850 --> 00:41:24.810
and then donate it to my Super PAC?

00:41:24.810 --> 00:41:25.942
- You can.

00:41:25.942 --> 00:41:28.193
(audience exclaims)

00:41:28.193 --> 00:41:29.120
(audience laughs)

00:41:29.120 --> 00:41:30.310
- But wait, wait.

00:41:30.310 --> 00:41:32.480
Super PACs are transparent.

00:41:32.480 --> 00:41:36.260
- Right--
- And the c4 is secret.

00:41:36.260 --> 00:41:39.480
So I can take secret donations off my c4

00:41:39.480 --> 00:41:42.460
and give it to my supposedly
transparent Super PAC.

00:41:42.460 --> 00:41:45.400
- And it'll say, "Given by your c4."

00:41:45.400 --> 00:41:48.190
- What is the difference between
that and money laundering?

00:41:48.190 --> 00:41:50.240
(audience laughs)

00:41:50.240 --> 00:41:51.832
- It's hard to say.

00:41:51.832 --> 00:41:52.800
(audience laughs)

00:41:52.800 --> 00:41:54.800
- Well, Trevor, thank you
so much for setting me up

00:41:54.800 --> 00:41:55.633
(audience cheers)
(audience applauds)

00:41:55.633 --> 00:41:57.395
in this brave new world.

00:41:57.395 --> 00:41:58.820
(gavel thuds)

00:41:58.820 --> 00:42:00.190
Dismissed.

00:42:00.190 --> 00:42:01.683
Trevor Potter, everybody.

00:42:03.530 --> 00:42:05.763
- So, he called it right.

00:42:06.880 --> 00:42:11.880
What we see after SpeechNow
is enter the Super PAC,

00:42:15.374 --> 00:42:17.730
and you have political action committees

00:42:17.730 --> 00:42:20.640
that can raise and spend
unlimited amounts of money

00:42:20.640 --> 00:42:24.740
from corporations, unions,
individuals, and associations,

00:42:24.740 --> 00:42:26.800
that is, from anyone.

00:42:26.800 --> 00:42:28.980
And so just people who are interested

00:42:28.980 --> 00:42:31.053
in the details of this,

00:42:31.990 --> 00:42:34.420
Super PACs can choose either to be

00:42:34.420 --> 00:42:39.420
what had been known as a
527 or a 501c4 organization.

00:42:41.460 --> 00:42:46.460
So the 527s, these had
been created by the IRS

00:42:48.360 --> 00:42:51.740
to allow organizations and committees

00:42:51.740 --> 00:42:56.250
to raise and spend money
specifically to influence politics,

00:42:56.250 --> 00:43:00.410
but they had to report
donors and contributions.

00:43:00.410 --> 00:43:03.920
So they accepted donor
lists would be made public

00:43:03.920 --> 00:43:06.000
in exchange for greater freedom

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:09.990
to directly influence election
initiatives, if you'd like.

00:43:09.990 --> 00:43:12.740
The 501c4, as you saw,

00:43:12.740 --> 00:43:17.210
that's what was being
described in the video,

00:43:17.210 --> 00:43:19.040
works a little differently.

00:43:19.040 --> 00:43:20.150
It's a nonprofit.

00:43:20.150 --> 00:43:23.820
It's just a little different from a 501c3,

00:43:23.820 --> 00:43:26.063
which is what Yale University is.

00:43:27.010 --> 00:43:28.567
It was created in 1913

00:43:33.370 --> 00:43:36.350
with the intention of
creating tax exemptions

00:43:36.350 --> 00:43:38.790
for civic and commercial organizations

00:43:38.790 --> 00:43:43.020
that focus exclusively on social welfare.

00:43:43.020 --> 00:43:46.900
And it can also collect unlimited funds,

00:43:46.900 --> 00:43:49.786
and here's what they were keying off of,

00:43:49.786 --> 00:43:53.640
it's 501c4s do not have to
disclose their donor lists.

00:43:53.640 --> 00:43:56.720
Basically, they forfeit their ability

00:43:56.720 --> 00:44:00.070
to engage in politics
as a primary function

00:44:00.070 --> 00:44:01.850
but they gain the ability

00:44:01.850 --> 00:44:05.143
to keep the sources of
their funding anonymous.

00:44:06.380 --> 00:44:09.020
Somewhere along the line, however,

00:44:09.020 --> 00:44:14.020
the interpretation of the 501c4
statute started to evolve.

00:44:15.170 --> 00:44:19.060
First of all, the word
exclusively educational

00:44:19.060 --> 00:44:22.410
came to mean primarily educational.

00:44:22.410 --> 00:44:27.100
And, of course, once you
have a word like primarily,

00:44:27.100 --> 00:44:30.863
you need lawyers to interpret
what does primarily mean.

00:44:33.620 --> 00:44:38.620
And somewhere along the
line, it seems, in the 1960s,

00:44:42.500 --> 00:44:47.500
the agencies started to
interpret primarily to mean 51%.

00:44:51.860 --> 00:44:55.090
It's not clear why, I've
done some digging into this.

00:44:55.090 --> 00:44:57.960
Perhaps there's a lobbying
story there, I don't know.

00:44:57.960 --> 00:45:02.640
But so what it basically means is that

00:45:04.678 --> 00:45:09.678
you've got to spend 51% on
your social welfare purpose,

00:45:11.630 --> 00:45:13.583
that gay people cause earthquakes,

00:45:14.620 --> 00:45:19.620
and you can then spend 49%
directly on political activity.

00:45:19.890 --> 00:45:24.550
And this is what gave rise
to the Lois Lerner scandal

00:45:24.550 --> 00:45:26.180
in the Obama administration,

00:45:26.180 --> 00:45:27.790
which some of you might remember.

00:45:27.790 --> 00:45:31.583
She was a mid-level operative in the IRS.

00:45:33.360 --> 00:45:37.320
They were getting floods and
floods of these new 501c4s.

00:45:37.320 --> 00:45:40.800
This was in the wake of
the Tea Party movement.

00:45:40.800 --> 00:45:44.320
And so she was tasked, or tasked herself,

00:45:44.320 --> 00:45:49.320
with investigating whether
they were doing the 49% or not.

00:45:49.420 --> 00:45:54.420
And she then got accused of
disproportionately investigating

00:45:56.470 --> 00:45:58.710
conservative 501c4s,

00:45:58.710 --> 00:46:01.440
and that blew up into
something of a scandal

00:46:01.440 --> 00:46:02.920
that went viral.

00:46:02.920 --> 00:46:06.350
Well, that was all generated by this law.

00:46:06.350 --> 00:46:09.220
So, in effect, what it's done is it's said

00:46:09.220 --> 00:46:11.760
that you can engage in
unlimited expenditures

00:46:15.620 --> 00:46:19.630
without disclosure, the
slide is misleading,

00:46:19.630 --> 00:46:21.890
I will fix it before I post it,

00:46:21.890 --> 00:46:25.150
while optional disclosure, I
guess is sufficient to say,

00:46:25.150 --> 00:46:28.243
without disclosure for 51%.

00:46:29.290 --> 00:46:32.140
Essentially paying a 51% quasi-tax.

00:46:32.140 --> 00:46:33.490
It's not really even a tax

00:46:33.490 --> 00:46:37.370
because you can define
your social welfare purpose

00:46:37.370 --> 00:46:38.993
to suit yourself.

00:46:39.890 --> 00:46:42.730
And so if you wanna see
what effect this had,

00:46:42.730 --> 00:46:47.480
this is Super PAC spending by disclosure.

00:46:47.480 --> 00:46:51.690
You can see that in the
2010 election cycle,

00:46:51.690 --> 00:46:54.593
before all of this became operative,

00:46:56.640 --> 00:47:01.640
most of the money was going
to companies that, whoops,

00:47:03.340 --> 00:47:07.220
to 527s that were disclosing

00:47:07.220 --> 00:47:10.470
and not very much was going to others.

00:47:10.470 --> 00:47:14.433
But after 2012, you can
see a lot more money

00:47:14.433 --> 00:47:19.340
started to go to the new 501c4 Super PACs,

00:47:19.340 --> 00:47:24.340
at least half of the spending
in that election cycle.

00:47:24.470 --> 00:47:29.470
So we've seen this is a
move into more dark money

00:47:29.610 --> 00:47:33.530
than we had had before
operating in politics.

00:47:33.530 --> 00:47:38.530
The upshot is that contributions
to candidates or campaigns

00:47:38.850 --> 00:47:41.830
can still be limited by
the federal government,

00:47:41.830 --> 00:47:45.010
but independent expenditures
can't be limited

00:47:45.010 --> 00:47:47.590
and contributions to organizations

00:47:47.590 --> 00:47:50.130
that engage in expenditures.

00:47:50.130 --> 00:47:52.310
So contributions to
candidates can be limited

00:47:52.310 --> 00:47:54.440
but contributions to organizations

00:47:54.440 --> 00:47:57.423
that engage in expenditures
cannot be limited,

00:47:58.460 --> 00:48:01.440
and reporting rules would require

00:48:01.440 --> 00:48:06.110
a massive overhaul to be meaningful.

00:48:06.110 --> 00:48:11.110
So that has been the story
of campaign finance reform

00:48:11.660 --> 00:48:16.420
in the American courts through 2010.

00:48:16.420 --> 00:48:19.553
I should mention one additional decision,

00:48:20.850 --> 00:48:23.310
and this is 2014

00:48:23.310 --> 00:48:27.390
McCutcheon v. the Federal
Election Commission.

00:48:27.390 --> 00:48:30.060
This is the only subsequent time

00:48:30.060 --> 00:48:33.090
the Court has revisited campaign finance.

00:48:33.090 --> 00:48:35.860
And there, there had been a law

00:48:35.860 --> 00:48:38.980
which had limited the number of candidates

00:48:38.980 --> 00:48:41.063
that you could give money to.

00:48:43.420 --> 00:48:45.630
I think it was to five candidates

00:48:45.630 --> 00:48:48.280
in any given election cycle,

00:48:48.280 --> 00:48:50.370
and the amount you could give to a party

00:48:50.370 --> 00:48:52.000
was also limited.

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:54.740
And so that meant the
total amount you could give

00:48:54.740 --> 00:48:59.623
in any two-year election
cycle came up to $117,200.

00:49:02.610 --> 00:49:04.310
You couldn't give more than that.

00:49:04.310 --> 00:49:09.310
And the Court said no,
why should you be limited

00:49:09.960 --> 00:49:13.330
to only giving to five candidates?

00:49:13.330 --> 00:49:16.570
The justification for
this combined restriction

00:49:16.570 --> 00:49:18.090
was unwarranted.

00:49:18.090 --> 00:49:21.950
It's not tailored to
any particular purpose

00:49:21.950 --> 00:49:25.653
that the government is
entitled to engage in.

00:49:26.690 --> 00:49:28.970
Even though, actually, Buckley had upheld

00:49:28.970 --> 00:49:32.580
aggregation limits, they said, again,

00:49:32.580 --> 00:49:34.720
there's no quid pro quo here,

00:49:34.720 --> 00:49:37.520
you're not giving money
to get anything in return.

00:49:37.520 --> 00:49:38.400
What's the difference

00:49:38.400 --> 00:49:40.980
between giving money to five candidates

00:49:40.980 --> 00:49:44.243
and giving money to 30 or 40 candidates?

00:49:45.310 --> 00:49:49.360
Again, assuming quid pro
quo is the only corruption

00:49:49.360 --> 00:49:51.020
worth worrying about.

00:49:51.020 --> 00:49:55.080
And a massive increase in inequality

00:49:55.080 --> 00:49:57.010
of contributing power now.

00:49:57.010 --> 00:50:02.010
Instead of 117,200, you
could give 3.5 million

00:50:03.800 --> 00:50:07.203
in contributions in any election cycle.

00:50:08.230 --> 00:50:13.230
So, again, much more
inequality of influence

00:50:13.630 --> 00:50:15.863
in the world of contributions.

00:50:17.340 --> 00:50:19.760
Now some people say this isn't so terrible

00:50:19.760 --> 00:50:23.230
because it may attract more money

00:50:23.230 --> 00:50:25.530
into contributions to candidates

00:50:25.530 --> 00:50:28.140
and less money into dark money.

00:50:28.140 --> 00:50:31.910
Rick Pildes at the NYU
Law School, for example,

00:50:31.910 --> 00:50:33.970
has made this argument.

00:50:33.970 --> 00:50:37.150
So the idea is that if you can give

00:50:37.150 --> 00:50:38.530
more money to the candidates,

00:50:38.530 --> 00:50:40.610
you won't spend it on dark money,

00:50:40.610 --> 00:50:44.073
and so we might actually
get less darkness.

00:50:44.945 --> 00:50:47.113
At this point, I think that's speculative.

00:50:50.275 --> 00:50:52.100
The jury is out.

00:50:52.100 --> 00:50:57.100
So that is the jot and tittle
of the Court's involvement

00:50:58.600 --> 00:51:03.030
in campaign finance reform efforts.

00:51:03.030 --> 00:51:05.260
Before I turn to the demand side,

00:51:05.260 --> 00:51:06.940
I just wanted to say something

00:51:06.940 --> 00:51:10.310
about the changing media
context of all of this

00:51:10.310 --> 00:51:14.970
because we're living in
a very different world

00:51:14.970 --> 00:51:18.570
from the world that existed in 1976.

00:51:18.570 --> 00:51:22.080
Apart from what we make of this equation

00:51:22.080 --> 00:51:24.840
of money with speech that Byron White

00:51:24.840 --> 00:51:28.780
and many others have
subsequently criticized.

00:51:28.780 --> 00:51:33.780
In 1976 there were
basically three TV channels.

00:51:34.500 --> 00:51:38.750
And because of the
scarcity of TV channels,

00:51:38.750 --> 00:51:42.310
the federal government came up with,

00:51:42.310 --> 00:51:45.780
this was not done through the
courts or even by Congress,

00:51:45.780 --> 00:51:48.250
it was actually done in
the executive branch,

00:51:48.250 --> 00:51:52.693
they came up with, the FEC
came up with something,

00:51:54.990 --> 00:51:59.990
it wasn't the SEC but it was,
I forget exactly which agency,

00:52:00.500 --> 00:52:02.330
but they came up with this,

00:52:02.330 --> 00:52:05.480
Federal Communications
Commission, the FCC,

00:52:05.480 --> 00:52:07.880
came up with something
called the fairness doctrine.

00:52:07.880 --> 00:52:11.100
And the notion there was that because

00:52:13.060 --> 00:52:16.120
there's a limited number of channels,

00:52:16.120 --> 00:52:21.120
that if a TV channel puts
on one point of view,

00:52:21.690 --> 00:52:23.960
they must put on a competing point of view

00:52:23.960 --> 00:52:25.210
from the other side.

00:52:25.210 --> 00:52:28.040
So there was this notion of achieving

00:52:28.040 --> 00:52:31.120
some kinds of political balance.

00:52:31.120 --> 00:52:33.590
And this was never actually
challenged in the courts

00:52:33.590 --> 00:52:36.950
so the Court never ruled on it,

00:52:36.950 --> 00:52:40.860
and we had the fairness
doctrine until the 1980s

00:52:40.860 --> 00:52:43.180
during the Reagan administration.

00:52:43.180 --> 00:52:45.260
And during the Reagan administration,

00:52:45.260 --> 00:52:48.053
we also had the advent
of cable television.

00:52:48.970 --> 00:52:52.430
And the FCC said, well, now

00:52:53.594 --> 00:52:56.160
there's an unlimited number of channels,

00:52:56.160 --> 00:52:59.940
so there's no reason to
have the fairness doctrine.

00:52:59.940 --> 00:53:03.830
And then we got satellite, so
instead of 80 or 90 channels

00:53:03.830 --> 00:53:05.270
we have hundreds of channels.

00:53:05.270 --> 00:53:08.040
So there's no reason to
have the fairness doctrine

00:53:08.040 --> 00:53:10.660
because the logic for
the fairness doctrine

00:53:10.660 --> 00:53:13.680
was the scarcity of channels.

00:53:13.680 --> 00:53:15.910
Now, there's no scarcity.

00:53:15.910 --> 00:53:20.280
In fact, more or less
unlimited number of channels.

00:53:20.280 --> 00:53:22.420
And so the Reagan administration

00:53:22.420 --> 00:53:25.360
abandoned the fairness doctrine

00:53:25.360 --> 00:53:30.017
and that started us on
the political consequences

00:53:31.880 --> 00:53:34.850
of increasingly segmented media markets.

00:53:34.850 --> 00:53:39.040
The world that we moved
to being a world in which

00:53:43.780 --> 00:53:46.690
liberals get their news from MSNBC,

00:53:46.690 --> 00:53:50.113
conservatives from Fox News or Breitbart,

00:53:51.137 --> 00:53:53.850
and then of course onto
the world of social media,

00:53:53.850 --> 00:53:58.587
the world of people getting
news from Facebook and so on.

00:54:00.840 --> 00:54:04.530
And so we're now in a world in which

00:54:06.912 --> 00:54:11.912
it's almost impossible
to have any requirement

00:54:12.410 --> 00:54:16.720
that different points of
view confront one another

00:54:16.720 --> 00:54:19.560
in the sense that, say, John Stuart Mill

00:54:19.560 --> 00:54:24.430
talked about in the competition for ideas,

00:54:24.430 --> 00:54:27.560
the idea that if you think about

00:54:30.780 --> 00:54:33.540
prime minister's questions
in the UK Parliament

00:54:34.791 --> 00:54:36.790
where the prime minister
has to stand there

00:54:36.790 --> 00:54:37.720
and be questioned

00:54:37.720 --> 00:54:41.690
and defend his or her
views to the opposition.

00:54:41.690 --> 00:54:45.850
We saw earlier Margaret
Thatcher defending her views

00:54:45.850 --> 00:54:50.560
against her Labour critics
when she was leaving office.

00:54:50.560 --> 00:54:52.170
We never have that now.

00:54:52.170 --> 00:54:54.330
Political speech is not about

00:54:54.330 --> 00:54:57.700
institutionalized argument over policies,

00:54:57.700 --> 00:55:01.450
it's rather about mobilizing
your own supporters.

00:55:01.450 --> 00:55:03.170
It's about you speak to the people

00:55:03.170 --> 00:55:04.730
who already agree with you.

00:55:04.730 --> 00:55:09.730
We know from Kahneman
and Sunstein's research

00:55:10.920 --> 00:55:12.670
that I referred to last time,

00:55:12.670 --> 00:55:15.580
that tends to make people more extreme.

00:55:15.580 --> 00:55:19.000
And so political speech is
really about mobilization,

00:55:19.000 --> 00:55:23.230
mobilization of people within your world

00:55:23.230 --> 00:55:25.450
of like-minded people,

00:55:25.450 --> 00:55:30.240
and not about argument over policy.

00:55:30.240 --> 00:55:35.240
And that is a development
that is underpinned

00:55:36.730 --> 00:55:39.600
by other changes in the political system

00:55:39.600 --> 00:55:43.080
that I'm going to get to briefly today

00:55:43.080 --> 00:55:46.030
but more fully later on.

00:55:46.030 --> 00:55:51.030
So let's look for the last few
minutes at the demand side.

00:55:52.170 --> 00:55:54.370
We've been talking this entire lecture

00:55:54.370 --> 00:55:55.480
about the supply side.

00:55:55.480 --> 00:55:58.960
We've been talking about why people

00:55:58.960 --> 00:56:01.010
wanna spend money on politics

00:56:01.010 --> 00:56:04.060
and what kind of influence
they think they can get

00:56:04.060 --> 00:56:06.483
from spending money on politics.

00:56:08.110 --> 00:56:11.450
Whether it corrupts the system or not

00:56:13.264 --> 00:56:15.960
and what sort of definition
of corruption we should have.

00:56:15.960 --> 00:56:20.400
But why is it that politicians want money?

00:56:20.400 --> 00:56:22.163
Why do they need so much money?

00:56:23.840 --> 00:56:27.610
We spend much more money
in politics in this country

00:56:27.610 --> 00:56:29.420
than in almost any other country.

00:56:29.420 --> 00:56:31.610
Why do politicians need money, yeah?

00:56:31.610 --> 00:56:33.560
- [Man] They attempt to
put out their message.

00:56:33.560 --> 00:56:38.560
They attempt to buy advertisement
from one side (mumbles).

00:56:39.192 --> 00:56:43.817
- Okay, so they want to
put out their message.

00:56:43.817 --> 00:56:47.610
But British and German and
Dutch and Australian politicians

00:56:47.610 --> 00:56:49.700
wanna put out their messages too

00:56:49.700 --> 00:56:53.270
and they don't have so much
need for money in politics.

00:56:53.270 --> 00:56:54.963
So any, why?

00:56:56.810 --> 00:56:58.153
Who else, okay, yeah?

00:57:05.876 --> 00:57:08.510
- [Man] There are no primaries in the UK

00:57:08.510 --> 00:57:11.833
and the election cycle
takes exactly six weeks.

00:57:13.840 --> 00:57:18.540
- So frequent elections
and a staggered cycle,

00:57:18.540 --> 00:57:20.103
as well as primaries.

00:57:20.103 --> 00:57:24.220
So we have essentially
permanent campaigning

00:57:24.220 --> 00:57:26.450
and campaigns are much longer.

00:57:26.450 --> 00:57:28.530
In most parliamentary systems,

00:57:28.530 --> 00:57:30.200
you call an election

00:57:30.200 --> 00:57:32.840
three or four weeks before the election.

00:57:32.840 --> 00:57:37.840
There's a very short election
cycle, so that's one reason.

00:57:39.740 --> 00:57:41.240
And of course, if you have primaries,

00:57:41.240 --> 00:57:43.360
you need money for the primaries.

00:57:43.360 --> 00:57:48.360
So those are among the reasons
people need so much money.

00:57:49.450 --> 00:57:51.053
Any other reasons?

00:57:53.240 --> 00:57:54.073
Yeah?

00:57:57.145 --> 00:57:59.570
- [Man] It's seen as a measure
of support for the candidate.

00:57:59.570 --> 00:58:02.750
- Seen as a measure of
support for a candidate.

00:58:02.750 --> 00:58:06.520
So we see how do you
get to be on the stage

00:58:06.520 --> 00:58:08.920
in the current democratic debates?

00:58:08.920 --> 00:58:10.650
You've got to not only show

00:58:10.650 --> 00:58:13.200
that you've risen to a
certain level in the polls,

00:58:13.200 --> 00:58:16.400
but you've also gotta
have raised enough money

00:58:16.400 --> 00:58:20.080
from some specified number
of independent contributors.

00:58:20.080 --> 00:58:24.913
So it's a way of demonstrating
that you can get support.

00:58:26.100 --> 00:58:31.100
Again, it's not obvious
why that differentiates

00:58:31.940 --> 00:58:35.190
American politics from other countries.

00:58:35.190 --> 00:58:36.023
Yeah?

00:58:37.980 --> 00:58:39.960
- [Woman] Well, for
presidential elections,

00:58:39.960 --> 00:58:42.850
this is a huge country
and people need to have

00:58:42.850 --> 00:58:44.290
teams all over the place.

00:58:44.290 --> 00:58:46.190
And unlike a parliamentary system

00:58:46.190 --> 00:58:49.060
where the local elections then govern

00:58:49.060 --> 00:58:51.680
who comes in power and so forth,

00:58:51.680 --> 00:58:55.710
here, you need to have a
completely national campaign,

00:58:55.710 --> 00:58:58.660
which becomes very, very expensive.

00:58:58.660 --> 00:59:01.503
- Well, I mean, you certainly,

00:59:03.184 --> 00:59:06.200
in many countries you have
to have national campaigns,

00:59:06.200 --> 00:59:10.840
and first and foremost, you
have to win in your district,

00:59:12.270 --> 00:59:15.310
you need the money to win
in your district here.

00:59:15.310 --> 00:59:19.810
But I think you're onto
something nonetheless

00:59:19.810 --> 00:59:21.590
about thinking about the difference

00:59:21.590 --> 00:59:25.383
between national campaigning
and local campaigning.

00:59:26.812 --> 00:59:28.062
There's a hand over here.

00:59:39.080 --> 00:59:42.305
- [Woman] I'm thinking about investments.

00:59:42.305 --> 00:59:45.150
So, like the stock market.

00:59:45.150 --> 00:59:49.000
Almost like maybe they'll
take in the finances

00:59:49.000 --> 00:59:51.720
and then invest in bigger corporations

00:59:51.720 --> 00:59:55.523
and look for those corporations
to put their name back out.

00:59:55.523 --> 00:59:57.823
It's almost like a partnership.

00:59:58.900 --> 01:00:02.420
- Well, I think focusing
on people investing

01:00:02.420 --> 01:00:06.060
is also part of it, and
political investing.

01:00:06.060 --> 01:00:07.780
Here's a way to think about it,

01:00:07.780 --> 01:00:12.780
that we have very weak
parties in the United States,

01:00:13.300 --> 01:00:18.150
and I'll say more about what
makes a party a weak party.

01:00:18.150 --> 01:00:20.030
Part of it is primaries.

01:00:20.030 --> 01:00:24.210
But a weak party is a party

01:00:24.210 --> 01:00:27.600
that is very decentralized in its control.

01:00:27.600 --> 01:00:32.600
So in a country with
stronger political parties,

01:00:33.010 --> 01:00:34.844
such as Britain,

01:00:34.844 --> 01:00:39.844
the party has a big say in who
the candidates are gonna be.

01:00:39.980 --> 01:00:42.650
They don't have primaries,
as somebody pointed out,

01:00:42.650 --> 01:00:44.130
we have primaries.

01:00:44.130 --> 01:00:46.993
So another way of putting it is,

01:00:47.860 --> 01:00:51.403
in our system all
campaigning has to be retail.

01:00:53.108 --> 01:00:56.440
And retail campaigning
is much more expensive

01:00:56.440 --> 01:00:58.340
than wholesale campaigning

01:00:59.600 --> 01:01:03.210
because every person
is running on their own

01:01:03.210 --> 01:01:04.410
for their own seat,

01:01:04.410 --> 01:01:07.310
and they need a lot of money to do that,

01:01:07.310 --> 01:01:11.123
and they can be threaded in
their own individual seat.

01:01:11.990 --> 01:01:15.540
Some of you probably heard
on the news this morning

01:01:15.540 --> 01:01:20.540
reports that there's some
35 Republicans in the Senate

01:01:21.010 --> 01:01:25.910
who privately would support

01:01:29.520 --> 01:01:31.760
convicting Donald Trump

01:01:31.760 --> 01:01:34.680
if the impeachment resolution
goes through the House,

01:01:34.680 --> 01:01:36.920
but publicly will not.

01:01:36.920 --> 01:01:39.340
And the reason, and people
come out and say it,

01:01:39.340 --> 01:01:44.340
they say, "If you did,
you would immediately face

01:01:44.727 --> 01:01:47.530
"a primary challenge in your district."

01:01:47.530 --> 01:01:51.390
And so everybody has to,

01:01:51.390 --> 01:01:53.830
if you'd like, in retail campaigning,

01:01:53.830 --> 01:01:55.870
it's every person for themself.

01:01:55.870 --> 01:01:59.140
In wholesale campaigning,
you're part of a team

01:01:59.140 --> 01:02:02.650
that is trying to win as a team.

01:02:02.650 --> 01:02:07.650
And so in our system, politicians
need vast amounts of money

01:02:10.430 --> 01:02:15.190
because they have to get elected retail.

01:02:15.190 --> 01:02:17.450
All politics is local.

01:02:17.450 --> 01:02:20.990
It's a famous American aphorism,

01:02:20.990 --> 01:02:24.270
but that means all politics is retail.

01:02:24.270 --> 01:02:27.680
So there might be benefits
of politics being local

01:02:27.680 --> 01:02:32.030
but the cost is that
politics is very expensive.

01:02:32.030 --> 01:02:37.030
And of course once you have
a lot of retail campaigning,

01:02:37.800 --> 01:02:39.780
it also turns raising money

01:02:39.780 --> 01:02:42.800
into something like an arms race,

01:02:42.800 --> 01:02:47.560
because if you don't raise
as much as your opponent,

01:02:47.560 --> 01:02:49.520
you're not gonna be able,

01:02:49.520 --> 01:02:52.840
you're not gonna be able
to have enough money

01:02:52.840 --> 01:02:55.070
perhaps to get on the debate stage

01:02:55.070 --> 01:03:00.070
or to get enough media
time in order to prevail.

01:03:01.050 --> 01:03:05.020
And so this is why public funding limits

01:03:05.020 --> 01:03:07.210
are so inadequate,

01:03:07.210 --> 01:03:10.373
because what happens is, no
matter where they're set,

01:03:11.310 --> 01:03:16.070
people soon discover that
they can raise more money

01:03:16.070 --> 01:03:17.940
if they don't take the public funding.

01:03:17.940 --> 01:03:21.140
The idea is if you take the public funds,

01:03:21.140 --> 01:03:25.890
then you've gotta limit your fundraising.

01:03:25.890 --> 01:03:30.890
But the last time the capital
was increased was before 2008

01:03:33.200 --> 01:03:36.130
and President Obama,
who was the first person

01:03:36.130 --> 01:03:38.610
to use crowdsource fundraising,

01:03:38.610 --> 01:03:41.700
realized very quickly that he
could raise a lot more money

01:03:43.715 --> 01:03:44.548
than the limit.

01:03:44.548 --> 01:03:45.480
I forgot what it was then,

01:03:45.480 --> 01:03:46.900
it was several hundred million dollars,

01:03:46.900 --> 01:03:51.500
but his was the first million-dollar
presidential campaign.

01:03:51.500 --> 01:03:55.580
So public funding limits don't work

01:03:55.580 --> 01:03:58.100
in a world in which people

01:03:58.100 --> 01:04:01.650
can raise as much
private money as possible

01:04:01.650 --> 01:04:06.210
and in a world in which you're basically

01:04:06.210 --> 01:04:09.670
trying to communicate
with your base voters,

01:04:09.670 --> 01:04:12.390
you're trying to communicate to the people

01:04:12.390 --> 01:04:14.303
who mostly agree with you.

01:04:15.990 --> 01:04:19.310
And so that's one of the reasons why

01:04:20.160 --> 01:04:23.490
we find it so difficult to limit

01:04:23.490 --> 01:04:26.780
the role of money in politics.

01:04:26.780 --> 01:04:28.710
Some other reasons

01:04:32.220 --> 01:04:35.850
why there's so much
demand for money is that,

01:04:35.850 --> 01:04:39.240
I said to you earlier
when I was talking about

01:04:40.090 --> 01:04:44.160
the resurgent right and
the anti-tax movement

01:04:44.160 --> 01:04:48.040
that a lot of those
bodies invested heavily

01:04:48.040 --> 01:04:51.560
in think tanks because they
thought the universities

01:04:51.560 --> 01:04:53.460
were dominated by the left

01:04:53.460 --> 01:04:56.600
and it'd be much efficient
to spend the money

01:04:56.600 --> 01:05:01.600
in places like Heritage, the
American Enterprise Institute,

01:05:02.280 --> 01:05:05.400
the Cato Institute, and so on.

01:05:05.400 --> 01:05:09.720
Now, a lot of money,
particularly in response to

01:05:11.090 --> 01:05:13.290
these recent Court decisions,

01:05:13.290 --> 01:05:16.163
is moving from the think tanks.

01:05:17.010 --> 01:05:20.160
The think tank gap between Republicans

01:05:20.160 --> 01:05:23.760
and Democratic think
tanks has closed somewhat

01:05:23.760 --> 01:05:28.540
and the money it seems is
going into these 501c4s,

01:05:28.540 --> 01:05:31.410
and that, again, means,

01:05:31.410 --> 01:05:34.450
from the point of view of
the arms race of politics,

01:05:34.450 --> 01:05:38.650
that your opponents are gonna
have more money spent on them

01:05:38.650 --> 01:05:43.650
and so you therefore need
to get it spent on yourself.

01:05:44.020 --> 01:05:48.410
And so, again, we find that the remedies

01:05:48.410 --> 01:05:50.963
sometimes make the problem worse.

01:05:54.330 --> 01:05:57.350
Another point just about the arms race.

01:05:57.350 --> 01:06:00.430
I think that this is an area

01:06:00.430 --> 01:06:02.340
that's actually right for reform

01:06:02.340 --> 01:06:05.010
because politicians hate it.

01:06:05.010 --> 01:06:10.010
They hate, if you do any
interviewing of candidates,

01:06:10.090 --> 01:06:12.010
you'll see this, politicians hate it

01:06:12.010 --> 01:06:15.630
because they have to spend
all their time raising money

01:06:15.630 --> 01:06:17.590
and because they're then controlled

01:06:17.590 --> 01:06:19.440
by the people who give them the money,

01:06:19.440 --> 01:06:20.590
and they don't like it.

01:06:21.457 --> 01:06:25.660
And the structure of an
arms race is you can't stop.

01:06:26.761 --> 01:06:29.750
Underneath it is something
called the prisoner's dilemma.

01:06:29.750 --> 01:06:31.560
Even though it would be in the interest

01:06:31.560 --> 01:06:33.793
of both of you to stop raising money,

01:06:34.880 --> 01:06:36.690
if you could agree to do that,

01:06:36.690 --> 01:06:39.190
the logic of the situation
keeps driving people

01:06:39.190 --> 01:06:41.890
to raise more and more and more money.

01:06:41.890 --> 01:06:44.520
And so actually politicians,

01:06:44.520 --> 01:06:46.520
the vast majority of them would like

01:06:46.520 --> 01:06:49.990
to get something to stop the arms race,

01:06:49.990 --> 01:06:54.557
which is why they passed
the campaign bill in 1974

01:06:55.750 --> 01:07:00.440
that we began with over
Gerald Ford's veto.

01:07:00.440 --> 01:07:04.000
And the reason is that they were trying

01:07:04.000 --> 01:07:06.560
to put a constraint on the arms race

01:07:06.560 --> 01:07:09.920
so that they wouldn't
have to raise this money.

01:07:09.920 --> 01:07:13.430
So but for the Court, this
problem wouldn't exist.

01:07:13.430 --> 01:07:17.940
And I think it's, as I
said, a salutary reminder

01:07:17.940 --> 01:07:22.663
of the cost of having
independent judiciaries.

01:07:25.890 --> 01:07:29.740
One final point is that
there's been a lot of talk

01:07:29.740 --> 01:07:32.210
about crowdsource funding.

01:07:32.210 --> 01:07:34.590
Maybe this is the antidote,

01:07:34.590 --> 01:07:38.830
this is the antidote to
big money in politics.

01:07:38.830 --> 01:07:40.430
You know, lots of millions and millions

01:07:40.430 --> 01:07:42.470
of little contributions, isn't that great?

01:07:42.470 --> 01:07:44.553
It's like democracy is in the streets.

01:07:46.120 --> 01:07:50.320
People can give one or $2 and, as I said,

01:07:50.320 --> 01:07:54.310
actually Barack Obama was the first person

01:07:54.310 --> 01:07:57.530
to use crowdsource funding in a big way.

01:07:57.530 --> 01:08:01.000
Bernie Sanders is very effective
at crowdsource funding.

01:08:01.000 --> 01:08:03.300
And so a lot of people have said, well,

01:08:03.300 --> 01:08:06.340
maybe there'll be a technical fix here

01:08:06.340 --> 01:08:11.340
that we will get to counterweight
the role of big money.

01:08:14.640 --> 01:08:18.080
But what the research shows is that

01:08:18.080 --> 01:08:21.860
even people who give small amounts

01:08:21.860 --> 01:08:25.520
tend to not be representatives
of their districts.

01:08:25.520 --> 01:08:29.320
They tend to be activists
on the fringes of parties,

01:08:29.320 --> 01:08:34.320
they tend to be people funding
groups like the Tea Party

01:08:36.980 --> 01:08:41.770
or groups on the far left
of the Democratic Party.

01:08:41.770 --> 01:08:46.770
So the idea that you're gonna
get less extreme views funded,

01:08:47.210 --> 01:08:49.000
particularly people who give any money

01:08:49.000 --> 01:08:51.040
outside of their own district

01:08:51.040 --> 01:08:52.610
tend to have very extreme views.

01:08:52.610 --> 01:08:56.130
Almost nobody gives money
outside their own district

01:08:56.130 --> 01:09:00.600
who doesn't have, is not on
extremes of their parties.

01:09:00.600 --> 01:09:05.150
So the idea that this is gonna
be a way to sort of restore

01:09:05.150 --> 01:09:07.970
the influence of the
median voter in politics

01:09:07.970 --> 01:09:12.360
is not something we should
get too excited about.

01:09:12.360 --> 01:09:16.350
On Thursday we're gonna turn
to part two of the course

01:09:18.120 --> 01:09:23.120
and we'll look at democracy's
fourth wave, question mark,

01:09:23.410 --> 01:09:28.063
as it emerged in the wake of the Cold War.

